    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "c3a16918_3fde83b2",
        "filename": "resultdb/sink/sink.go",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 117,
      "author": {
        "id": 1147264
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-28T23:01:13Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "This class is public and Validate() is also public. It implies that users are free to declare ServerConfig{}, and invoke Validate() without going through NewServer().\n\nIf there was NewServerConfig() and SetDefaultValues() were called inside NewServerConfig(), then it\u0027d make sense to make it private, but there isn\u0027t. Perhaps, we could just make Validate() as private.\n\nWDYT?",
      "parentUuid": "111e736c_3e66d157",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 117,
        "startChar": 23,
        "endLine": 117,
        "endChar": 24
      },
      "revId": "c11643ecd5b61cc93904ce5272b01db641e321db",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "d7062610_55b9f14d",
        "filename": "resultdb/sink/sink.go",
        "patchSetId": 6
      },
      "lineNbr": 117,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114299
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-08-29T20:19:24Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "+1 to making Validate() private.\n\nI can see a use case for having Validate() public, e.g. ServerSettings are a part of another struct, and that struct has Validate(), which needs to call this Validate()\n\nbut I SetDfeaultValues() exists only because it is an implementation detail of this package. The alternative implementation to have the following code where we use individual fields\n\n  val :\u003d c.myField\n  if val \u003d\u003d 0 {\n    val \u003d DefaultForMyField\n  }\n  // use val\n\nthen we wouldn\u0027t have SetDefaultValues() to begin with",
      "parentUuid": "c3a16918_3fde83b2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 117,
        "startChar": 23,
        "endLine": 117,
        "endChar": 24
      },
